u202f13) to include a detail string:\\n\\n```python\\nraise HolidayAgentException(\\n    \\\"Google Maps API failed\\\",\\n    f\\\"Status code {response.status_code}, response: {response.text}\\\"\\n)\\n```\\n\\n### 3\ufe0f\u20e3 Use a more Pythonic built\u2011in exception\\n\\nIf you don\u2019t need a custom class, you could simply raise a built\u2011in exception with a rich message:\\n\\n```python\\nraise RuntimeError(\\n    f\\\"Google Maps API failed \u2013 status {response.status_code}: {response.text}\\\"\\n)\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Step\u2011by\u2011step debugging guide\\n\\n1. **Open `GoogleMap.py`** and locate line\u202f13 (the line that raises the exception).  \\n2. **Check the definition** of `HolidayAgentException` (usually near the top of the file or in a shared `exceptions.py`).  \\n3. **Decide** whether you want the second argument to be mandatory or optional.  \\n4. **Apply one of the fixes** above.  \\n5. **Run the script again** (or run the specific function that calls the Google Maps API) to verify the error is gone.  \\n\\n---\\n\\n## Example \u2013 Full corrected snippet\\n\\nBelow is a minimal, self\u2011contained version of what the file might look like after applying the most flexible fix (making `error_detail` optional).\\n\\n```python\\n# GoogleMap.py\\nimport requests\\n\\nclass HolidayAgentException(Exception):\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"Custom exception for the HolidayAgent project.\\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    def __init__(self, error_message: str, error_detail: str = \\\"\\\"):\\n        super().__init__(error_message)\\n        self.detail = error_detail\\n\\n    def __str__(self):\\n        # Show both parts when the exception is printed\\n        base = super().__str__()\\n        return f\\\"{base} | Detail: {self.detail}\\\" if self.detail else base\\n\\n\\ndef get_place_coordinates(place_name: str, api_key: str):\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    Calls the Google Maps Geocoding API and returns (lat, lng).\\n    Raises HolidayAgentException on any failure.\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    endpoint = \\\"https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json\\\"\\n    params = {\\\"address\\\": place_name, \\\"key\\\": api_key}\\n    try:\\n        response = requests.get(endpoint, params=params, timeout=10)\\n        response.raise_for_status()          # raises HTTPError for 4xx/5xx\\n        data = response.json()\\n\\n        if data.get(\\\"status\\\") != \\\"OK\\\":\\n            raise HolidayAgentException(\\n                \\\"Google Maps API returned non\u2011OK status\\\",\\n                f\\\"status={data.get('status')}, error_message={data.get('error_message')}\\\"\\n            )\\n\\n        location = data[\\\"results\\\"][0][\\\"geometry\\\"][\\\"location\\\"]\\n        return location[\\\"lat\\\"], location[\\\"lng\\\"]\\n\\n    except requests.RequestException as exc:\\n        # Network\u2011level problems (timeout, DNS, connection error, etc.)\\n        raise HolidayAgentException(\\n            \\\"Failed to reach Google Maps API\\\",\\n            str(exc)\\n        ) from exc\\n\\n\\n# ----------------------------------------------------------------------\\n# Example usage (remove or guard with if __name__ == \\\"__main__\\\" in prod)\\nif __name__ == \\\"__main__\\\":\\n    API_KEY = \\\"YOUR_GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY\\\"\\n    try:\\n        lat, lng = get_place_coordinates(\\\"Baga Beach, Goa, India\\\", API_KEY)\\n        print(f\\\"Baga Beach \u2192 lat: {lat}, lng: {lng}\\\")\\n    except HolidayAgentException as e:\\n        print(f\\\"\u274c Error: {e}\\\")\\n```\\n\\n**What changed?**\\n\\n| Change | Reason |\\n|--------|--------|\\n| `error_detail: str = \\\"\\\"` in `__init__` | Makes the second argument optional, preventing the \u201cmissing argument\u201d error when you only pass a message. |\\n| `__str__` override | Gives a nice printable representation that includes the detail when it exists. |\\n| Wrapped the request in a `try/except` and re\u2011raised a `HolidayAgentException` with both a message **and** the original exception text. | Provides richer debugging info without breaking the flow. |\\n\\n---\\n\\n## How to test the fix quickly\\n\\n```bash\\npython - <<'PY'\\nfrom GoogleMap import get_place_coordinates, HolidayAgentException\\n\\ntry:\\n    # Intentionally use a bad API key to trigger the exception path\\n    get_place_coordinates(\\\"Calangute Beach, Goa\\\", api_key=\\\"INVALID_KEY\\\")\\nexcept HolidayAgentException as e:\\n    print(\\\"Caught custom exception:\\\")\\n    print(e)               # Should show both message and detail\\nPY\\n```\\n\\nYou should see something like:\\n\\n```\\nCaught custom exception:\\nGoogle Maps API returned non\u2011OK status | Detail: status=REQUEST_DENIED, error_message=The provided API key is invalid.\\n```\\n\\nIf you get that output, the exception class works as intended and the original \u201cmissing argument\u201d error is resolved.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Next steps for your project\\n\\n1. **Search for other places** where `HolidayAgentException` is raised and verify they now pass the correct number of arguments (or rely on the default).  \\n2. **Add unit tests** for the exception handling path so future refactors will surface similar mismatches early.  \\n3. **Consider logging** the `error_detail` to a file or monitoring system (e.g., using Python\u2019s `logging` module) instead of only printing it.  \\n\\n---\\n\\n### TL;DR\\n\\n*Your custom exception expects two arguments, but you only gave one.*  \\n**Fix:** either make the second argument optional (`error_detail: str = \\\"\\\"`) **or** always supply a second argument when raising the exception. The example above shows a clean, production\u2011ready implementation.  \\n\\nIf you run into any other traceback lines or need help wiring this into the larger HolidayAgent workflow, just drop the next error message here and we\u2019ll keep debugging together! \ud83d\ude80\",\"type\":\"TextMessage\"},\"inner_messages\":[]},\"name\":\"Travel_Planner\"}", "sender": "Travel_Planner_9c0d9cc4-2e89-41de-9105-53542349de34/9c0d9cc4-2e89-41de-9105-53542349de34", "receiver": null, "kind": "MessageKind.PUBLISH", "delivery_stage": "DeliveryStage.DELIVER", "type": "Message"}
