else base\\n```\\n\\nNow you can raise it with **one** or **two** arguments:\\n\\n```python\\nraise HolidayAgentException(\\\"Google Maps API failed\\\")                     # detail = \\\"\\\"\\nraise HolidayAgentException(\\\"Google Maps API failed\\\", \\\"Timeout\\\")         # detail = \\\"Timeout\\\"\\n```\\n\\n### 2\ufe0f\u20e3 Always pass a second argument (enforce richer errors)\\n\\nIf you want every raised exception to carry extra context, modify the raise site to include a detail string.\\n\\n```python\\nraise HolidayAgentException(\\n    \\\"Google Maps API failed\\\",\\n    f\\\"Status code {response.status_code}, response: {response.text}\\\"\\n)\\n```\\n\\n### 3\ufe0f\u20e3 Use a built\u2011in exception instead of a custom one\\n\\nIf the custom class isn\u2019t needed, you can simply raise a standard exception with a full message.\\n\\n```python\\nraise RuntimeError(\\n    f\\\"Google Maps API failed \u2013 status {response.status_code}: {response.text}\\\"\\n)\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Step\u2011by\u2011step debugging guide\\n\\n1. **Open `GoogleMap.py`.**  \\n   Locate the line that raises the exception (line\u202f13 in the traceback).\\n\\n2. **Find the definition of `HolidayAgentException`.**  \\n   It\u2019s usually near the top of the file or in a shared `exceptions.py`.\\n\\n3. **Decide which fix you want:**  \\n   *Make the second argument optional* (Option\u202f1) is the least invasive and works for all existing raise statements.  \\n   *Always pass a detail* (Option\u202f2) gives you richer logs but requires updating every raise site.  \\n   *Switch to a built\u2011in exception* (Option\u202f3) removes the custom class entirely.\\n\\n4. **Apply the change.**  \\n   - For Option\u202f1, edit the class definition as shown above.  \\n   - For Option\u202f2, edit the `raise` line to include a second argument.  \\n   - For Option\u202f3, replace `raise HolidayAgentException(...)` with `raise RuntimeError(...)`.\\n\\n5. **Run a quick test** (see the snippet below) to confirm the error is gone.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Example \u2013 Full corrected snippet (Option\u202f1)\\n\\n```python\\n# GoogleMap.py\\nimport requests\\n\\nclass HolidayAgentException(Exception):\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"Custom exception for the HolidayAgent project.\\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    def __init__(self, error_message: str, error_detail: str = \\\"\\\"):\\n        super().__init__(error_message)\\n        self.detail = error_detail\\n\\n    def __str__(self):\\n        base = super().__str__()\\n        return f\\\"{base} | Detail: {self.detail}\\\" if self.detail else base\\n\\n\\ndef get_place_coordinates(place_name: str, api_key: str):\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    Calls the Google Maps Geocoding API and returns (lat, lng).\\n    Raises HolidayAgentException on any failure.\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    endpoint = \\\"https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json\\\"\\n    params = {\\\"address\\\": place_name, \\\"key\\\": api_key}\\n    try:\\n        response = requests.get(endpoint, params=params, timeout=10)\\n        response.raise_for_status()          # raises HTTPError for 4xx/5xx\\n        data = response.json()\\n\\n        if data.get(\\\"status\\\") != \\\"OK\\\":\\n            raise HolidayAgentException(\\n                \\\"Google Maps API returned non\u2011OK status\\\",\\n                f\\\"status={data.get('status')}, error_message={data.get('error_message')}\\\"\\n            )\\n\\n        location = data[\\\"results\\\"][0][\\\"geometry\\\"][\\\"location\\\"]\\n        return location[\\\"lat\\\"], location[\\\"lng\\\"]\\n\\n    except requests.RequestException as exc:\\n        # Network\u2011level problems (timeout, DNS, connection error, etc.)\\n        raise HolidayAgentException(\\n            \\\"Failed to reach Google Maps API\\\",\\n            str(exc)\\n        ) from exc\\n\\n\\n# ----------------------------------------------------------------------\\n# Quick sanity test (run this block directly)\\nif __name__ == \\\"__main__\\\":\\n    API_KEY = \\\"YOUR_GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY\\\"\\n    try:\\n        lat, lng = get_place_coordinates(\\\"Baga Beach, Goa, India\\\", API_KEY)\\n        print(f\\\"Baga Beach \u2192 lat: {lat}, lng: {lng}\\\")\\n    except HolidayAgentException as e:\\n        print(f\\\"\u274c Error: {e}\\\")\\n```\\n\\n**What changed?**\\n\\n| Change | Why it matters |\\n|--------|----------------|\\n| `error_detail: str = \\\"\\\"` in `__init__` | Makes the second argument optional, eliminating the \u201cmissing argument\u201d error when only a message is supplied. |\\n| `__str__` override | Gives a readable string that includes the detail when it exists, helpful for logging/debugging. |\\n| Wrapped the request in a `try/except` and re\u2011raised a `HolidayAgentException` with both a message **and** the original exception text. | Provides richer context without breaking the flow. |\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Quick test you can run right now\\n\\n```bash\\npython - <<'PY'\\nfrom GoogleMap import get_place_coordinates, HolidayAgentException\\n\\ntry:\\n    # Use an obviously bad API key to trigger the error path\\n    get_place_coordinates(\\\"Calangute Beach, Goa\\\", api_key=\\\"INVALID_KEY\\\")\\nexcept HolidayAgentException as e:\\n    print(\\\"Caught custom exception:\\\")\\n    print(e)               # Should show both message and detail\\nPY\\n```\\n\\nYou should see something like:\\n\\n```\\nCaught custom exception:\\nGoogle Maps API returned non\u2011OK status | Detail: status=REQUEST_DENIED, error_message=The provided API key is invalid.\\n```\\n\\nIf you get that output, the exception class works correctly and the original `TypeError` is resolved.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Next steps for your project\\n\\n1. **Search the codebase** for any other `raise HolidayAgentException(...)` statements and verify they either now pass a second argument or rely on the optional default.  \\n2. **Add unit tests** that deliberately cause a failure (e.g., bad API key, network timeout) and assert