2026-02-20 20:38:08 - INFO - 574 -{"payload": "{\"response\":{\"chat_message\":{\"id\":\"4a60c2e6-1ffb-44bb-99b4-b1f9b39cb1f7\",\"source\":\"Travel_Planner\",\"models_usage\":{\"prompt_tokens\":5865,\"completion_tokens\":1457},\"metadata\":{},\"created_at\":\"2026-02-20T15:08:08.586943Z\",\"content\":\"## TL;DR  \\nYour custom exception `HolidayAgentException` is defined to require **two** arguments (`error_message`\u202fand\u202f`error_detail`).  \\nAt line\u202f13 you raise it with only one argument, so Python throws  \\n\\n```\\nTypeError: HolidayAgentException.__init__() missing 1 required positional argument: 'error_detail'\\n```\\n\\n### Two clean ways to fix it  \\n\\n| Fix | When to use | What to change |\\n|-----|-------------|----------------|\\n| **1\ufe0f\u20e3 Make `error_detail` optional** (most flexible) | You don\u2019t always have extra context, but you still want the custom class. | Add a default value (`\\\"\\\"`) to the second parameter in the class definition. |\\n| **2\ufe0f\u20e3 Always pass a second argument** (enforce richer errors) | You want every raised exception to carry extra debugging info. | Modify every `raise HolidayAgentException(...)` call to include a detail string. |\\n| **3\ufe0f\u20e3 Drop the custom class** and use a built\u2011in exception | The custom class isn\u2019t needed elsewhere. | Replace `raise HolidayAgentException(...)` with `raise RuntimeError(...)` (or another built\u2011in). |\\n\\nBelow are the exact code changes for **Option\u202f1** (the least invasive and works with all existing raise statements).\\n\\n---\\n\\n## \u2705 Option\u202f1 \u2013 Make `error_detail` optional  \\n\\n### 1\ufe0f\u20e3 Update the exception class (usually at the top of `GoogleMap.py` or in a shared `exceptions.py`)\\n\\n```python\\nclass HolidayAgentException(Exception):\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    Custom exception for the HolidayAgent project.\\n    `error_detail` is optional so the exception can be raised with just a message.\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    def __init__(self, error_message: str, error_detail: str = \\\"\\\"):\\n        super().__init__(error_message)\\n        self.detail = error_detail\\n\\n    def __str__(self) -> str:\\n        base = super().__str__()\\n        return f\\\"{base} | Detail: {self.detail}\\\" if self.detail else base\\n```\\n\\n*Key change:* `error_detail: str = \\\"\\\"` gives the second argument a default value, eliminating the \u201cmissing argument\u201d error when you only pass a message.\\n\\n### 2\ufe0f\u20e3 (Optional) Keep your existing raise statements unchanged  \\n\\n```python\\n# line 13 \u2013 still works\\nraise HolidayAgentException(\\\"Google Maps API failed\\\")\\n```\\n\\nIf you **do** have extra context, you can now add it without breaking anything:\\n\\n```python\\nraise HolidayAgentException(\\n    \\\"Google Maps API failed\\\",\\n    f\\\"Status {response.status_code}: {response.text}\\\"\\n)\\n```\\n\\n### 3\ufe0f\u20e3 Full\u2011file example (with a tiny wrapper around the Google Maps call)\\n\\n```python\\n# -------------------------------------------------\\n# GoogleMap.py\\n# -------------------------------------------------\\nimport requests\\n\\nclass HolidayAgentException(Exception):\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"Custom exception for the HolidayAgent project.\\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    def __init__(self, error_message: str, error_detail: str = \\\"\\\"):\\n        super().__init__(error_message)\\n        self.detail = error_detail\\n\\n    def __str__(self) -> str:\\n        base = super().__str__()\\n        return f\\\"{base} | Detail: {self.detail}\\\" if self.detail else base\\n\\n\\ndef get_place_coordinates(place_name: str, api_key: str):\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    Calls the Google Maps Geocoding API and returns (lat, lng).\\n    Raises HolidayAgentException on any failure.\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    endpoint = \\\"https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json\\\"\\n    params = {\\\"address\\\": place_name, \\\"key\\\": api_key}\\n    try:\\n        response = requests.get(endpoint, params=params, timeout=10)\\n        response.raise_for_status()          # HTTP 4xx/5xx \u2192 raise\\n        data = response.json()\\n\\n        if data.get(\\\"status\\\") != \\\"OK\\\":\\n            raise HolidayAgentException(\\n                \\\"Google Maps API returned non\u2011OK status\\\",\\n                f\\\"status={data.get('status')}, error_message={data.get('error_message')}\\\"\\n            )\\n\\n        location = data[\\\"results\\\"][0][\\\"geometry\\\"][\\\"location\\\"]\\n        return location[\\\"lat\\\"], location[\\\"lng\\\"]\\n\\n    except requests.RequestException as exc:\\n        # Network\u2011level problems (timeout, DNS, connection error, etc.)\\n        raise HolidayAgentException(\\n            \\\"Failed to reach Google Maps API\\\",\\n            str(exc)\\n        ) from exc\\n\\n\\n# ----------------------------------------------------------------------\\n# Quick sanity test (run this block directly)\\nif __name__ == \\\"__main__\\\":\\n    API_KEY = \\\"YOUR_GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY\\\"\\n    try:\\n        lat, lng = get_place_coordinates(\\\"Baga Beach, Goa, India\\\", API_KEY)\\n        print(f\\\"Baga Beach \u2192 lat: {lat}, lng: {lng}\\\")\\n    except HolidayAgentException as e:\\n        print(f\\\"\u274c Error: {e}\\\")\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## \ud83d\udccb How to verify the fix\\n\\n1. **Run a tiny test** that forces an error (e.g., use an invalid API key).  \\n\\n```bash\\npython - <<'PY'\\nfrom GoogleMap import get_place_coordinates, HolidayAgentException\\n\\ntry:\\n    get_place_coordinates(\\\"Calangute Beach, Goa\\\", api_key=\\\"BAD_KEY\\\")\\nexcept HolidayAgentException as e:\\n    print(\\\"Caught custom exception:\\\")\\n    print(e)   # Should show both message and detail\\nPY\\n```\\n\\n2. **Expected output** (exact wording may differ, but you should see a message *and* a detail part):\\n\\n```\\nCaught custom exception:\\nGoogle Maps API returned non\u2011OK status | Detail: status=REQUEST_DENIED, error_message=The provided API key is invalid.\\n```\\n\\nIf you see the exception printed without a `TypeError`, the fix is successful.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## \ud83c\udfaf Next steps for your project\\n\\n1. **Search the repo** for any other `raise HolidayAgentException(...)` lines and confirm they either:  \\n   * now work with the optional `error_detail`, **or**  \\n   * are updated to pass a second argument (if you prefer richer logs).  \\n\\n2. **Add unit tests** that deliberately cause a failure (bad key, network timeout) and assert that a `HolidayAgentException` is raised and that `e.detail` is non\u2011empty.  \\n\\n3. **Consider logging** the `detail` field to a file or monitoring system (e.g., using Python\u2019s `logging` module) so you have a persistent record of API failures.  \\n\\n---\\n\\n## Need anything else?\\n\\n* Want the **second\u2011argument\u2011mandatory** version instead?  \\n* Need help wiring this into a larger \u201cHolidayAgent\u201d workflow?  \\n* Want a quick script that automatically retries the Google Maps call on transient errors?\\n\\nJust let me know and I\u2019ll dive right in! \ud83d\ude80\",\"type\":\"TextMessage\"},\"inner_messages\":[]},\"name\":\"Travel_Planner\"}", "sender": "Travel_Planner_9c0d9cc4-2e89-41de-9105-53542349de34/9c0d9cc4-2e89-41de-9105-53542349de34", "receiver": null, "kind": "MessageKind.PUBLISH", "delivery_stage": "DeliveryStage.DELIVER", "type": "Message"}
